Introduction to Open Data Science - Course Project

About the project

This is the course diary for the course Introduction to Data Science, organized by University of Helsinki in Fall 2022. Here I will update my progress on the course, as well as the actual course work during the next six weeks. I heard about the course through a mailing list and it caught my attention as it is could support my research. I do empirical research in macroeconomics and therefore I deal with large data sets on a daily basis. This is why it is useful for me to learn new routines and ideas on data management.

Chapter 3

library(tidyverse)
alc <- read_csv("data/alc.csv")

Q2

The data set consists of 35 variables of 370 students in secondary education of two Portugese schools. This survey data were gathered in 2014. The data are discrete and consist of 14 binary and 21 non-binary covariates describing student backgrounds. Examples of the former are access to internet or to family educational support and, of the latter, time used for travelling to school or for weekly studies. The number of unique values per variable as well as the variable names are given in the graph below. We see that there is considerable variation in the non-binary variables, with the minimum and maximum number of unique values in this group being 3 and 26, respectively.

tibble(n_uniq = apply(alc, 2, function(x) length(unique(x))),
       var_name = names(n_uniq)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n_uniq, y=var_name)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_discrete(limits=rev) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(5,25, by=5)) +
  xlab("Number of unique values per variable") +
  ylab("Variable names")

Q3

I choose two variables from both groups of binary and non-binary variables. Chosen variables from the former group are parents’ cohabitation status and access to extra educational support, while, of the latter group, I choose the number of past failures and home to school travel time. I expect that the parents’ living apart and no access to extra educational support are positively correlated with higher alcohol use. Finally, I expect that the number of past failures and home to school travel time are positively correlated with the alcohol use.

Q4

To explore the relationship between alcohol use and the chosen covariates, I use two different graphical tools. In the first one, I set the binary variables in the x-axis and the shares of each group denoting the alcohol use on a scale 1 to 5 stacked in the y-axis. This facilitates an easy comparison between the groups even though the numbers of cases between the binary variables vary. We would expect that the bars on the left have larger share of small values than those in the right.

We see that the postulated hypothesis on the relationship between the binary variables and alcohol use might not be as strong as expected. In the both cases, the proportion of the respondents having alcohol use below level 2 is almost the same. Moreover, the proportion of respondents having the highest level of alcohol use (5) is considerably higher with respondents with access to educational support, which is surprising. In summary, the relationship between these binary variables and alcohol use is very weak.

alc <- alc %>%
  mutate(Pstatus = map_chr(.x = Pstatus, ~ifelse(.x=="A", "Apart", "Together"))) 
alc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = factor(alc_use, levels = as.character(seq(5, 1, by = -0.5))),  
             y = alc_use, 
             x = factor(Pstatus, levels = c("Together", "Apart")))) + 
  geom_bar(position="fill", stat="identity") + 
  ylab("Alcohol use by proportion conditioned on the group") +
  xlab("Parents' cohabitation status ") +
  scale_fill_discrete(guide="none") -> p1

alc <- alc %>%
  mutate(schoolsup = map_chr(.x = schoolsup, ~ifelse(.x=="yes", "Yes", "No"))) 
alc %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = factor(alc_use, levels = as.character(seq(5, 1, by = -0.5))), 
             y = alc_use, 
             x = factor(schoolsup, levels = c("Yes", "No")))) + 
  geom_bar(position="fill", stat="identity") + 
  ylab("") +
  xlab("Access to educational support") +
  scale_fill_discrete("Alcohol use") -> p2
gridExtra::marrangeGrob(list(p1,p2), nrow = 1, ncol = 2, top = NULL)

Second, I use the box plots to describe the relationship between alcohol use (y-axis) and the non-binary covariates (x-axis), which both are given conveniently four distinct values. Here we see a considerably stronger relationship between alcohol use and the chosen covariates. The median values (denoted by the vertical line in the bar) increase with the travel time to school and past failures. Also, we see that the 25th percentile of the groups, which have the highest values for both travel time to school and past failures, are above the 75th percentiles of the groups with the smallest values in these categories. These indicate stronger relationship between alcohol use and the chosen covariates.

alc %>% ggplot(aes(x = traveltime, y=alc_use, group=traveltime)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylab("Alcohol use (1-5)") +
  xlab("Travel time to school (1-4)") -> p1
alc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = failures, y=alc_use, group = failures)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ylab("") +
  xlab("Past failures (0-3)") -> p2
gridExtra::marrangeGrob(list(p1,p2), nrow = 1, ncol = 2, top = NULL)

Q5

The logistic regression results are given below. Two remarks are in order. First, the results confirm the earlier intuition that there is no strong linear relationship between the binary variables and alcohol use. The coefficients of the regression are not different from zero at the conventional significance levels. Second, the graphical intution of the non-binary variables is confirmed and the alcohol use appears to be linearly dependent on the non-binary covariates. Both of the coefficients pertaining to the non-binary variables are different from zero at the 5 percent significance level, as shown in the column for p-values.

glm_obj <- glm(high_use ~ Pstatus + schoolsup + traveltime + failures, data = alc, family = "binomial")
glm_obj %>% broom::tidy() %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, round, 4) %>% DT::datatable()

Next, below are the odds ratios calculated from the previous regression model. The odds ratios of the non-binary variables are above one and do not contain one in their 95 percent confidence intervals, and this confirms that the association between alcohol use and the non-binary variables. In summary, there is higher relative risk in using high amounts of alcohol with longer distance to school and past fails compared to those with shorter distance to school and fewer past failures, keeping the other variables fixed.

OR <- coef(glm_obj) %>% exp
CI <- confint(glm_obj) %>% exp()
cbind(OR, CI) %>% round(4) %>% DT::datatable()

library(MASS)

data(Boston)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

smr_tbl <- apply(Boston, 2, summary)

The summaries and associated box plots of the variables are given below. Q4

data_std <- as_tibble(Boston) %>% 
  mutate(across(!chas, ~(.x-mean(.x))/sd(.x)))
smr_tbl <- apply(data_std, 2, summary)
cor_mt <- cor(data_std)

The standardised data (apart from dummy variable chas) are shown below. The standardisation does not remove any outliers but renders the variables to same scale. This helps detecting further properties of the data from with the boxplot, such as rm having fatter tails in comparison to other variables. For the same skewed variables as mentioned before, one could entertain a logarithmic transformation to remove the strongly skewed nature of certain variables.

DT::datatable(apply(smr_tbl, 2, round, digits = 2))
boxplot(as.matrix(data_std), cex.axis = 0.65)

data_std <- data_std %>% 
  mutate(crime = cut(data_std$crim, breaks =  quantile(data_std$crim), include.lowest = TRUE)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-crim) %>% 
  mutate(train = (1:n())%in%sample(x = 1:n(), size = n()*0.8))
levels(data_std$crime) <-  c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high")

Q5

Q6

The predictions from the LDA model are given below. We see that the classes low and high are predicted accurately from the predictors. On the other hand, classes med_low and med_high are quite poorly predicted by the model. Especially, class med_low is predicted in less than half of the cases correctly.

lda.pred <- predict(lda_obj, newdata = data_std %>% dplyr::select(-crime) %>% filter(!train))

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = data_std$crime[!data_std$train], predicted = lda.pred$class)

Q1

human <- read_csv("data/human.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)
smr_tbl <- apply(human %>% dplyr::select(-Country), 2, summary)
cor_mat <- cor(human %>% dplyr::select(-Country) %>% as.matrix)

The variables are summarized below in figures giving the individual values per variable, summaries per variable, and correlation matrix between the variables. First, we see that the variable vary by order of magnitudes as gross national income takes values up to 1.23124^{5}, while the the ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education has the smallest value at 0.17. The bar plot shows also that the Adolescent birth rate , GNI and Maternal mortality ratio are skewed to the right as they are more “sparse”, i.e. have many observations, which are above the mean. This can be confirmed from the summary table. Finally and not surprisingly, we see clearly that the Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate vary negatively with variables associated with good quality of life, such as income, life expectancy and expected years of schooling.

human %>%
  # Switch to "long" format w. 'Country' as identifier
  pivot_longer(-Country, names_to = "Variable", values_to = "Value") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = Value, width=1)) + 
  # plot data on bar plot
  geom_bar(stat='identity', fill = "forest green") + 
  # 4x2 matrix of barplots
  facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 4, nrow = 2, scales = "free_y") +
  # remove the country names, they clutter the output
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank()) +
  # Take out the labels
  xlab("") +
  ylab("")

DT::datatable(apply(smr_tbl, 2, round, digits = 2))
corrplot::corrplot(cor_mat, diag = FALSE, type='lower')

Q2

Below, I give two figures to visualize the PCA. The scree plot shows how much each principal component accounts for the total variance of the variables. We see that the first PC accounts for virtually all of the variance in the data. This can be confirmed from the biplot, in which only one arrow is visible, as the others would have length zero. This PC corresponds to the varible GNI, which is of two or three orders of magnitudes larger than the other variables. Therefore, the analysis using the non-standardized variables makes little sense here.

pca_human <- prcomp(human %>% dplyr::select(-Country))
var_explained <- pca_human$sdev^2 / sum(pca_human$sdev^2)
qplot(x = 1:8, y = var_explained) + 
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("Principal Component") + 
  ylab("Variance Explained") +
  ggtitle("Scree Plot") +
  ylim(0, 1)

biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2)

Q3

In the below figures I repeat the analysis of Q2 but now with standardised data. Now we see that the first two PCs account for around 65% of the variance in the data, with the remaining six PCs accounting for the rest. Therefore, the data are quite well summarized using two PCs, as the line of the scree plot becomes quite flat after the second or third PC. This way of calculating the PCs is much more informative as we can give clearer interpretations to different PCs.

pca_human <- human %>% 
  # Select only numeric cols
  dplyr::select(-Country) %>% 
  # S'dize data
  mutate_all( ~ (.x-mean(.x))/sd(.x)) %>% 
  prcomp() 
# calculate the variance explained per variable
var_explained <- pca_human$sdev^2 / sum(pca_human$sdev^2)
# them agains the number of PCs (8)
qplot(1:8, var_explained) + 
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("Principal Component") + 
  ylab("Variance Explained") +
  ggtitle("Scree Plot") +
  ylim(0, 1)

pca_human %>% biplot(choices = 1:2)

Q4

The two PCs accounting for the majority of the variation in the data can be classified easily into two groups. The first relates to the general development of the country. They summarize the variation in variables relating to maternal mortality, life expectancy, income, and education level. The second PC relates to two highly interlinked variables, i.e. adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality ratio. The link between the two is expected to be strongly positive, which is also shown in the earlier correlation plot. The two PCs point towards opposite directions, which confirms the negative relationship between the variables belonging to the two first PCs. The two remaining variables pointing north in the plot explain little variation in the data (as seen from the correlation plot too), and are separated from the rest of the variables.

In this data set, I pick randomly ten out of 36 variables for the multiple correspondence analysis. The data are categorical and shown in figure below. The unique values per variable vary from two to six. Some the variables exhibit little variation, e.g. dinner, while variable price varies considerably more.

# calculate the number of cases per factor for each variable
get_counts <- apply(tea_rd, 2, table)
plot_list <- list()
for(jj in 1:10){
  # run a loop over the variables s.t. for each var a bar plot is created
  plot_list[[jj]] <- tibble(count = get_counts[[jj]], char = names(get_counts[[jj]])) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=char, y = count)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill = "forest green") +
    xlab("") +
    ylab("") +
    ggtitle(names(get_counts)[jj]) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45),
          plot.title = element_text(size = 8))

}
# plot variables in a 2-by-5 matrix
gridExtra::marrangeGrob(plot_list, nrow = 2, ncol = 5, top = FALSE)

Below I conduct MCA and explore the results verbally and visually. The figure shows that the principal inertia is 10.5% for the first dimension and 9.5% for the second. Together, they account for 20% of the variation in the data. Therefore, it can be concluded that the variables are not strongly correlated with each other. This conclusion can be confirmed by looking at the MCA factor map. The factors of each variable are quite randomly located along the two dimensions. I would continue on exploring the data to find some more reasonable relationships between the variables.

mca <- FactoMineR::MCA(as.matrix(tea_rd), graph = FALSE)
plot(mca, invisible="ind", graph.type = "classic", habillage = "quali")

library(tidyverse)
library(lme4)
BPRSL <- read_csv("data/BPRSL.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% 
  mutate(treatment = factor(treatment)) %>% 
  mutate(subject = factor(subject)) 
RATSL <- read_csv("data/RATSL.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% 
  mutate(ID = factor(ID)) %>% 
  mutate(Group = factor(Group))

Q1

In this exercise we analyze nutritional data on three groups of rats. The weight of the rats were observed over a time span of 64 days, and the weight was measured every seven days. The development of the weight over the sample span is depicted below. We see that the weights of the rats increase over time, as expected. The first group has the smallest development in weights in absolute terms. The interest is then if there is some differences in the means between the groups. This would indicate differences in the effectiveness of different diets.

RATSL %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Time, y = Weight, linetype = ID, color = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  # fix line types across individuals
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(RATSL$ID)), 3)) +
  # add color to better distinguish between individuals
  scale_color_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(RATSL$ID)), 3)) + 
  # set plots apart across Group
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  # remove legend
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  # set scale y-axis 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$Weight), max(RATSL$Weight)))

To analyze the question more carefully, the weights are standardized with respect to the measurement time and the resulting values are plotted below. This helps to see if the individuals with higher starting weight tend to have higher weight throughout the sample period. The development of the standardised weight appears approximately the same in nutrition group 1. In groups 2 and 3, there are more variation across the individuals, as is seen from the different slopes of the lines in these two panels.

RATSL <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(stdwght = (Weight - mean(Weight))/sd(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup()
RATSL %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Time, y = stdwght, linetype = ID, color = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  # fix line types across individuals
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(RATSL$ID)), 3)) +
  # add color to better distinguish between individuals
  scale_color_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(RATSL$ID)), 3)) + 
  # set plots apart across Group
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  # remove legend
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  # set scale y-axis 
  scale_y_continuous(name = "stadardized weight",
                     limits = c(min(RATSL$stdwght), max(RATSL$stdwght)))

Next, we analyze the means of the groups. This makes the analysis easier as the objects of interest per time period is reduced to three. The interest is whether the means differ across the time periods. Two thins stand out. First, the mean of group 1 is substantially smaller from those of groups 2 and 3, and does not increase substantially across the sample span. Second, the means of groups 2 and 3 largely overlap. The slopes of the time series are positive and develop similarly. This would indicate that there is no substantial difference in the nutritional effect of these diets.

RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  # no need to use summarise() here if data is grouped
  mutate(mean = mean(Weight),
         se = sd(Weight)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Time, y = mean, linetype = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=0.3) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight) +/- se(weight)")

Next, we analyse the question of equal means by box plots. The intuition of last figure is confirmed: group 1 has substantially smaller mean from the rest of the groups. Group two has an outlier value, which is removed from the analysis in the remainder.

RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  mutate(mean=mean(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight), Days 8-64")

RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  mutate(mean=mean(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  # filter out the possible outlier
  filter(mean < max(mean)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight), Days 8-64")

To test the hypothesis of equal means across the groups, we perform a simple t-test. The null hypothesis of equal means is rejected at the conventional significance levels (p-value <0.01). Therefore, the visual evidence was not supported by the formal hypothesis testing.

anova_data <- RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise(mean=mean(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  # filter out the possible outlier
  filter(mean < max(mean)) %>% 
  filter(Group%in%c(2,3))

t.test(mean ~ Group, data=anova_data,var.equal=TRUE)

Next, we assess the relationship between the mean weights and their development throughout the sample period using linear regression. The analysis below point towards the conclusion that the mean of the weights has increased across the individuals and time periods as the coefficient for baseline is positive and different from zero at the standard confidence levels. This is also backed by the anova-table, which lends support for the conclusion that the coefficients of the linear model are jointly different from zero at 99.9% level.

ols_data <- RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise(mean=mean(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  #add baseline group
  mutate(baseline = RATSL %>% filter(Time==1) %>% pull(Weight))

fit <- lm(mean ~ Group + baseline, data = ols_data)
summary(fit)

Q2

In this question we analyze data on males answering psychological questionnaire across eight weeks, based on which they were given scores (BPRS). They were given different treatments (coded in the data as treatment:1 or treatment:2). The results of individuals across the sample span is plotted below. The general trend is somewhat downwards. However, the individual differences across the ratings are large.

BPRSL %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Week, y=BPRS, linetype=subject, color=subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  # fix line types across individuals
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(BPRSL$subject)), 2)) +
  # add color to better distinguish between individuals
  scale_color_manual(values = rep(1:length(unique(BPRSL$subject)), 2)) + 
  # set plots apart across Group
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  # remove legend
  theme(legend.position = "none")

The preliminary analysis on the effect of treatment and the BPRS scores involves a linear regression where the underlying assumption is that the individuals are independent across time. The preliminary results lend support that test scores are decreasing with time, while the differences between groups are non-significant.

Going forward, we analyse the model by including a random slope for the variable Week. This allows even more general interpretation of the predictions. It controls for the different score development profiles between the individual males. The random slope has a considerably smaller variance than that of the random intercept of the individuals. Looking at the differences between the model fit we see that the random slope model is preferred to only random intercept at the 95% confidence level, as seen by the likelihood ratio test (p-value \(\approx\) 0.025).

BPRS_ref1 <- lmer(BPRS ~ Week + treatment + (Week | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

Finally, we explore if the inclusion of the interaction term capturing the combination of the week and treatment improve the fit. The improvement is modest. The LR test statistic is approx. 3.1 with 1 degrees of freedom yielding a p-value of about 0.075. Therefore, the simpler model is perhaps preferred in this instance.

BPRS_ref2 <- lmer(BPRS ~ Week + treatment + Week*treatment + (Week | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)
